    #title Asking Question Was Necessary In the Ancient Philosophical Tradition     
 
    %p To fully develop a response to the broad question "what is ancient philosophy?" is much too large a project to be undertaken in the provided word limit. As such, rather than attempting to answer the question "what is ancient philosophy?", I will argue in support of my own related thesis: asking questions was the starting point for reasoning in the ancient philosophical tradition (herein refered to as <b>AQ</b>). This thesis is not as broad reaching as would be a thesis attempting to fully answer "what is ancient philosophy", however <b>AQ</b>'s smaller, more modest scope will be able to be fully developed within the word limit.  Following, in order to defend my thesis, firstly in (<b>I</b>), I will explain one assumption my thesis rests upon, treating philosophical practice as a philosophical conversation. Next in (<b>II</b>) and (<b>III</b>),  I will add support for my thesis by examing philosophical reasoning exhibited by Plato and Zeno of Elea. Finally, concluding in (<b>IV</b>), I will present one potentional counter-argument against <b>AQ</b>. 

    %h2 I. AQ's Bare Assumption: Philosophical Practice is a Conversation
    %p To either, grant or deny <b>AQ</b>, one must first accept one assumption that <b>AQ</b> requires: Philosophical practice is the act of engaging in philosophical conversation (whether this is internally in one's own head, by writing down thought, or by conversing with others). As such, philosophical practice is nothing we cannot transcribe into language, as all philosophical conversation necessarily takes place langauge. Thus, when we refer to philosophical practice we are talking about in isolation the formalized conversation of philosophy between one to oneself or between one and another.  
    %p With this assumption established, it is also critical that I specify that the <i>ancient philosophical tradition</i> referenced in <b>AQ</b> refers to the ancient philosophical practices of, however not limtited to: Socrates, Aristotle, Zeno of Elea, and Plato. With these clarifications made, if we accept this assumption that philosophical practice is the act of enganging in philosophical conversation, the philosophical conversation must start somewhere. <b>AQ</b> simply suggests that the starting place for ancient philosophical conversation was asking questions.

    %h2 II. Plato's Naivete Sense of Wisdom Lends Support to AQ
    %p Plato argued that being a philosopher required a naivete-sense of wisdom. This naivete-sense of wisdom suggested that the philosopher be <i>truthful</i> with themselves at all times in admitting what they know and what they don't know. Thus, Plato argued that to be wise is to have a certain sense of honesty with one self. In an encounter with a politician Plato recounts, Plato claims himself to be wiser than the politician not because of what he knew, but because of what he was willing to admit he did not know. Plato admits "It's likely that neither of us knows anything fine and good", however he goes on to state that "I'm wiser than he in...one small way: that what I don't know, I don't think I know" (<i>Apology</i> &para;21D).
    %p What enabled Plato to state here "what I don't know, I don't think I know", was his asking of the question (either implicitly or explicitly): "what do I know?". Without asking the question, "what do I know?", how could Plato have formed the belief, that "what I don't know, I don't think I know" (<i>Apology</i> &para;21D). In other words, how may one reason about what one knows, without asking oneself, what oneself knows? As such, Plato's naivete sense of wisdom is brought forth through asking the question "what do I know?". Later, after this question is asked in Plato's philosophical conversation, Plato may make inferences about what he knows. But as a pre-requestite he must have necessarily asked the question, "what do I know?".  Thus, Plato's naivete sense of wisdom is simply one side-effect of accepting philosophy to be a conversation and accepting asking questions as the starting point to the conversation in adherence with <b>AQ</b>.

