    %h2 III. Support from Zeno of Elea for AQ
    %p Zeno of Elea similarly to Plato, used asking questions as the starting point of his philosophical practice and conversation. In Zeno's philosophical conversation he states "if anyone could make clear.. what the one is, he would be able to speak of the things that are" (<i>Zeno of Elea</i> &para;2). Like in the example with Plato, we may again attempt to determine the question Zeno of Elea needed to have asked in philosophical conversation to arrive at reasoning about "who would be able to say what the one is". The pre-requistive question Zeno must have asked is "what is the one?". Backtracking philosophical conversation as I have done here and in the previous example seems to simply and logically follow. Further, it would be hard to understand how else philosophical conversation could come about without such reasoning.
    %p In addition to this kind of backtracking approach to understanding the starting point for philosophical conversation I have taken in the previous two examples to show <b>AQ</b>, Zeno of Elea can also be seen explicitly asking questions as the start of the philosophical process. Zeno explicitly asks the question, "if place exists, where is it?" (<i>Zeno of Elea</i> &para;12). Later, Zeno expands this philosophical conversation to derive "for everything that exists is in a place. Therefore, place exists, then place is in a place." (<i>Zeno of Elea</i> &para;12). Examples of these more explicit questions supportive of <b>AQ</b> can be seen sprinkled throughout many both ancient and modern philosophical texts. Implicitally or explicitally, the start of the philosophical conversation always seems to be asking questions. At a more meta-level, even this philosophy paper, which is an example of philosophical practice and thus a philosophical conversation can be seen adhering to <b>AQ</b> in asking questions as the start of the philosophical conversation. In order for me to have argued favorable for <b>AQ</b>, first I needed to ask the quesiton: what was the starting point for asking philosophical questions in the ancient philosophical tradition?



    %h2 IV. Counter-Argument: AQ is not supported by implicit examples in (II) and (III)
    %p There may be a potential objection to my positive support of <b>AQ</b> in (II) and (III) suggesting that since I implied Plato and Zeno of Elea to ask questions in starting the philosophical conversation where I did not actually provide textual reference, I am guilty of falaciously begging the question to support <b>AQ</b>. As such, it is not necessarily the case that questions were asked to start the philosophical conversation and thus the conversation may have begun elsewhere; not by asking questions as <b>AQ</b> suggests. 
    %p I think this counter-argument holds weight, however, I pose the question: if questions are not the start of the philosophical conversation, how does philosophical converstion start? If there is a more reasonable way for philosophical conversation to initiate I am open to hearing a suggestion and adequately modifying <b>AQ</b>. However, it would seem difficult still, if not impossible, to give a descriptive account of where philosophical conversation starts separate from a normative account of where philosophical conversation <i>ought</i> to start. As such, in light of this counter-argument, <b>AQ</b> still holds weight, although I will concede that <b>AQ</b> is not a descriptive account but merely a normative account of where philosophical conversation starts. 

